result.execSummary:
The defendant Cheyenne R. Dick was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony [Modifiers: Repeater], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).
  • Criminal Damage to Property [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
If agent recommends, defendant must attend and successfully complete an alcohol assessment and comply with any recommended treatment.  Defendant is to execute any releases necessary for agent to verify compliance.

Defendant to be subject to random testing by his agent.

If agent recommends, defendant must attend and successfully complete a drug assessment, and comply with any recommended treatment.  Defendant to execute any releases necessary for agent to verify compliance.

Defendant to be subject to random testing by his agent.

The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by a risk and needs assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions. 

64 days sentence credit, if revoked.

Must seek and maintain full-time employment or a combination of employment and education which is satisfactory to your probation agent.  Defendant  must not leave or change employment without prior approval of your probation agent.

You must submit to and successfully complete a mental health evaluation to determine appropriate programming commensurate with needs identified.  Must comply with all recommendations.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.
Until further order of the court, you shall have no contact, directly or indirectly, either personally, by mail, telephone or through any other person, or by any other means with Victims.

Defendant may apply for expungement if probation successfully completed and all court obligations are satisfied. 

If Defendant has no new charges, no holds, and after the first year no other rule violations, no obligations, and has completed all conditions at the conclusion of the supervision, she could then be granted expungement for each of these charges.

If probation is revoked and a prison term is not ordered, or if probation is discharged or terminated, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of any restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt. Must pay all costs of supervision and court ordered financial obligations during the term of probation. 

The defendant is ORDERED  to report to the Jackson County Jail to submit the required DNA specimen. Contact the Jackson County Sheriff's Department at 715-284-5357 to arrange for an appointment.

8:35 AM Defendant Cheyenne R. Dick in court, in custody from JCJ.  Attorney Carly June Sebion in court for Cheyenne R. Dick.  Attorney Emily Hynek in court for State of Wisconsin. State in compliance with victim rights issues. Motion to amended Count 1 to Misd. Defendant enters a plea of No Contest to Count 1, repeater. Priors correct. 
22CF50 - Defendant enters a plea of No Contest to Ct 1, as repeater. No contest to Ct 2 as a repeater. 21CM121 and all other charges DRI. 

Court reviewed the elements and potential penalties of the charge the defendant plead to.  She understood.   Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant. Felony warnings given.  She understood. Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered her plea and waived her constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of 21CF172 - Battery contrary to 940.19(1), 939.62(1)(b) repeater. 22CF50 found guilty of Bail Jumping-Felony contrary to 946.49(1)(b), 939.62(1)(b) repeater, Count 2 - Criminal Damage to Property contrary to 943.01(1), 939.62(1)(a) repeater. 22CF50 victim restitution request. Defendant did not exercised her right to allocution. 

Joint recommendation: Sentence withheld,  3 yrs probation w/conditions of costs, DNA, AODA and follow through, risk and needs assessment. 22CF50 pay Restitution of $300.00 to victim. Eligible for expunction should def  successfully complete all requested treatment , no new charges or DOC holds. No contact w/victims, seek and maintain employment. 64 days credit on both counts. 

Court adopts joint recommendation:  Sentence withheld,  3 yrs probation w/conditions of costs pay thru probation, DNA,  AODA and follow through, mental health counseling, risk and needs assessment. 22CF50 pay Restitution of $300.00 plus costs to victim. Eligible for expunction if Defendant has no new charges, no holds, and after the first year no other rule violations, no obligations, and has completed all conditions at the conclusion of the supervision, she could then be granted expungement for each of these charges. Report to probation before noon. 

No contact w/victims, Seek and maintain employment/education. 64 days sentence credit on both counts.
